HUMAN ENTEROVIRUS D68 - NORTH AMERICA: UPDATE
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Tue 30 Mar 2015
Source: The Denver Post [edited]
http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_27816168/colorado-california-child-paralysis-cases-linked-new-enterovirus


Researchers said [Mon 29 Mar 2015] that comprehensive genetic analysis of enterovirus D68 [EV-D68] has strengthened the link between the pathogen and the sudden partial paralysis of children in Colorado and California. EV-D68 was suspected in the cases of dozens of children who lost some limb movement after bouts of respiratory illness in a widespread viral outbreak that began in August [2014].

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reports there were 115 cases in 34 states. The biggest cluster was in Colorado, which had 12 cases.

A team led by University of California San Francisco scientists said it had analyzed sequences of EV-D68 taken from 25 children stricken with the sudden-onset partial paralysis, called acute flaccid myelitis. The 25 paralysis cases in the study spanned outbreaks from 2012 to 2014. 9 of the samples analyzed in the study were from Colorado children; 16 were from California. Acute flaccid myelitis affected only a tiny percentage of children who came down with viral respiratory illness during outbreaks. Later, magnetic resonance imaging would show distinctive spinal cord lesions in these children. The children had been infected with a relatively new strain of EV-D68 that emerged about 4 years ago, designated strain B1, according to the study published [Mon 30 Mar 2015] in The Lancet Infectious Diseases journal [see item 3 below].

"We were quite surprised," said lead investigator Dr Charles Chiu, director of the UCSF-Abbot Viral Diagnostics and Discovery Center. The strain B1 has mutations similar to those found in poliovirus and another closely related nerve-damaging virus, EV-D70, he said. Only about half of the 25 children's samples were positive for EV-D68, which Chiu said is likely the result of delayed tissue-sample collection in the other half. Chiu said the team couldn't identify any other pathogens that could have caused the paralysis symptoms.

"Even after checking patient cerebrospinal fluid for every known infectious agent -- they looked for all possible things and didn't find anything else that could have caused it," said Dr. Samuel Dominguez of Children's Hospital Colorado, who submitted samples for the study. He participated in the analysis along with Children's Dr Kevin Messacar.

B1 was the predominant strain circulating during the 2014 EV-D68 respiratory outbreak, Chiu said. Researchers found it in both respiratory secretions and, for the 1st time, in a blood sample from one child. Scientists haven't found EV-D68 in cerebrospinal fluid, which would provide the strongest evidence yet it caused the polio-like symptoms. But it is difficult to detect viruses in cerebrospinal fluid, Chiu said. "Finding (EV-D68) in the bloodstream gives us a mechanism that had been missing before that could explain how the virus got to the spinal cord," Dominguez said.

However, that isn't the only possibility. Neurological symptoms are the result of an aberrant immune response to recent EV-D68 infection and not because the virus directly invades neurons, Chiu said. "I don't think we've answered it one way or another," Chiu said. He said more urgent investigation of the virus is needed. "None of the children with acute flaccid myelitis have fully recovered," he said.

At Children's Hospital Colorado, experts from multiple disciplines have created a clinic to follow the progress of the local cases.

[Byline: Electa Draper]

